{"parse":{"title":"Secondary cremation","pageid":27086708,"revid":789052120,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Primary cremation</b>  and <b>secondary cremation</b> are terms in <a href=\"/wiki/Archaeology\" title=\"Archaeology\">archaeology</a> for describing <a href=\"/wiki/Burial\" title=\"Burial\">burials</a> of  <a href=\"/wiki/Cremation\" title=\"Cremation\">cremated</a> bodies.\n</p><p>Primary cremation refers to burials where the body is burned \"on the spot\", in the grave. A secondary cremation is the burning of the body in one spot and then burying the remains and <a href=\"/wiki/Grave_good\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Grave good\">grave goods</a> elsewhere. Secondary cremation may also more specifically refer to a cremation where the body is burned on a <a href=\"/wiki/Pyre\" title=\"Pyre\">pyre</a>, after which the bones are collected from the ashes and buried elsewhere (Sprague 2005:138). A famous account of such a burial is that of <a href=\"/wiki/Homer\" title=\"Homer\">Homer</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Iliad\" title=\"Iliad\">Iliad</a></i>, describing the funeral of <a href=\"/wiki/Patroclus\" title=\"Patroclus\">Patroclus</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Secondary_cremation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Roderick Sprague, <i>Burial terminology: a guide for researchers</i>, Rowman Altamira, 2005, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7591-0841-7\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-7591-0841-7\">978-0-7591-0841-7</a>.</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1274\nCached time: 20180909171550\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time u